      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

What if Elon Musk had never made a hostile bid to buy Twitter Inc.? What if=
 Twitter was just bopping along, being a public company, and then one day i=
ts former head of security, Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko,  sent a b=
unch of regulators=C2=A0a whistle-blower letter saying that Twitter=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0security was bad in various ways, that it failed to safeguard use=
r data and was vulnerable to hackers and was generally sort of sloppy about=
 stuff? Obviously some things would happen:
=09Regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Federal Trade Commission, the Securities a=
nd Exchange Commission, etc. =E2=80=94 would investigate. If Twitter=E2=80=
=99s security was bad in the ways that Zatko says, then perhaps there would=
 be fines, or settlements requiring Twitter to change its practices.=C2=A0=
=09Politicians would hold hearings. Obviously politicians love to hold hear=
ings about how social-media companies are bad at privacy or moderation, so =
they=E2=80=99d do that here. It seems unlikely that anything would come of =
this.=09Perhaps there would be business consequences. Twitter users, disgus=
ted by its lax security practices, might quit. Advertisers might stop buyin=
g ads.=C2=A0=09Given these things =E2=80=94=C2=A0investigations, potential =
fines, bad publicity, business consequences =E2=80=94=C2=A0there would=C2=
=A0definitely=C2=A0be shareholder lawsuits. Everything,=C2=A0I am always sa=
ying around here, is securities fraud: If a public company does a bad thing=
 (bad information security practices, etc.), then shareholders can sue, say=
ing =E2=80=9Cyou did a bad thing but didn=E2=80=99t tell me about it, so I =
was tricked into buying stock, which is fraud.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

What would be the aggregate impact of all of those things? Well, I don=E2=
=80=99t know; it depends on how true and how serious Zatko=E2=80=99s claims=
 turn out to be. Twitter denies and downplays them, while Zatko has incenti=
ves to play them up. But so far my sense is that all of this is pretty ordi=
nary-course stuff. If you are a large social media company, there will be i=
nternal controversies about your information-security and content-moderatio=
n practices; every big social media company faces tradeoffs there. The peop=
le who lose out in those controversies will have incentives to go public as=
 whistle-blowers, and then regulators and politicians will have incentives =
to investigate and extract settlements. None of this is=C2=A0existential; n=
one of it is, like, =E2=80=9C90% of Twitter users are bots and so advertise=
rs=C2=A0will all leave,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CTwitter sold all of its users=
=E2=80=99 Social Security numbers to North Korean hackers so the users will=
 all quit,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CTwitter is operating illegally and will be =
shut down by the government.=E2=80=9D And most of it is pretty hypothetical=
, more =E2=80=9CTwitter=E2=80=99s practices create risks of something reall=
y bad happening=E2=80=9D than =E2=80=9Csomething really bad has actually ha=
ppened.=E2=80=9D
That doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily mean that all of Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint=
s are wrong or trivial. It=E2=80=99s just that, in a world where Twitter wa=
s just a public company with an information-security whistle-blower, the co=
nsequences of that would be pretty bounded. Might Twitter pay, I don=E2=80=
=99t know, nine digits of fines? Might it lose some business? Might its sto=
ck drop by 5%? Might a shareholder lawsuit settle for another nine digits? =
Again, without really having a strong view on the validity or seriousness o=
f these claims, I will say: Sure, those things are possible.
Might Twitter pay 11 digits of fines? Might it lose 30% of its business? Mi=
ght its stock drop by 30%? From this complaint? No, I am going to say, not =
really. It=E2=80=99s not literally impossible, but it=E2=80=99s not really =
a thing that happens. In particular, people don=E2=80=99t roll the dice on =
big investigations and lawsuits. They settle, for reasonable amounts of mon=
ey. There is a sense in which a certain amount of regulatory fines and cong=
ressional hearings and shareholder lawsuits are a cost of doing business fo=
r big tech companies: They can be expensive and annoying and one tries to m=
inimize them, but you can=E2=80=99t expect to escape them entirely, or worr=
y=C2=A0too=C2=A0much about them when they happen. This stuff seems to be in=
 that category.
But in the actual world we live in, where Musk did=C2=A0sign an agreement t=
o buy Twitter that he is now trying to get out of, things are different. Tw=
itter,=C2=A0now, is pretty much a binary bet. Either Musk will buy Twitter =
for $54.20 per share in cash, as he agreed to do in April, or he won=E2=80=
=99t. If he does, Twitter is worth $54.20 per share, to its existing shareh=
olders, and all this information-security stuff is Elon Musk=E2=80=99s (bou=
nded, manageable) problem. If he doesn=E2=80=99t, then Twitter is worth=C2=
=A0much less=C2=A0than $54.20 per share. What that number is =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0maybe it is $25? $30?=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0will depend on Twitter=E2=80=
=99s user growth and ad revenue and business prospects and legal liabilitie=
s and so forth, and perhaps Zatko=E2=80=99s complaints will lower that numb=
er by a dollar or two. But if you are a Twitter shareholder, that is a seco=
ndary concern; what is much more important to you is that $54.20 is much mu=
ch bigger than whatever that number is. You want the $54.20.
And Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint might make it harder for you to get it. Yeste=
rday Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers  sent Twitter another letter, re-terminating th=
e merger agreement, arguing that=C2=A0Twitter has breached the merger agree=
ment in various ways based on Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint, which Musk say =E2=
=80=9Calleges far-reaching misconduct at Twitter =E2=80=A6 that is likely t=
o have severe consequences for Twitter=E2=80=99s business.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0(T=
witter  sent a letter back to Musk saying =E2=80=9Cno.=E2=80=9D) Like Musk=
=E2=80=99s previous letter terminating the merger agreement for an unrelate=
d list of reasons, this letter is a strange piece of work =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=
 misrepresents what the merger agreement says for some reason?
  [1]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it certainly says a lot of things. If Zatko=E2=80=
=99s complaints are all true and maximally bad, then,   as we discussed yes=
terday, Musk might have some argument that he can get out of the deal for f=
raud. He=C2=A0might=C2=A0also have an argument that he can get out of the d=
eal for some failure of Twitter=E2=80=99s representations in the merger agr=
eement, and this letter opens up that argument.
Will it work? Man, I have no idea. When Musk previously tried to terminate =
the merger agreement, Twitter sued to force him to close, and that case is =
