The basic business of an activist investor is that you pick a public compan=
y, you buy a bunch of its stock, you announce your position, you say =E2=80=
=9CI have a few suggestions for how this company could be run better,=E2=80=
=9D you get the company to implement your suggestions (by persuasiveness, o=
r public pressure, or proxy fight),=C2=A0the suggestions are in fact good, =
and the stock goes up. Your suggestions increase the long-term value of the=
 company, which is good for the stock price today. You are a big shareholde=
r, so you profit. When you are done =E2=80=94=C2=A0when the company has imp=
lemented your changes and the stock price reflects the increased long-term =
value =E2=80=94=C2=A0you sell your stock and collect, as it were, your payc=
heck for a job well done.
Obviously it is possible to be bad at this. You might be bad at getting com=
panies to implement your suggestions =E2=80=94=C2=A0you are not persuasive,=
 you don=E2=80=99t win proxy fights, people don=E2=80=99t like you, etc. =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0or you might be good at getting them to implement your sugge=
stions, but the suggestions are bad and make the stock go down. But let=E2=
=80=99s assume that some people are good at it. What that means is that, wh=
en they announce an activist position in a company=E2=80=99s stock, (1) the=
y are likely to make changes to that company and (2) those changes are like=
ly to make the stock go up.=C2=A0
What=C2=A0that=C2=A0means is that, when they announce an activist position =
in a company=E2=80=99s stock, the stock will go up right away. Other invest=
ors will say =E2=80=9Cah, yes, that activist is in the stock, and her track=
 record is good, so this stock will go up, so I should buy it now,=E2=80=9D=
 so they do, so it goes up now.
If you are a good activist, this might create some temptation. You just spe=
nt, I don=E2=80=99t know, $100 million buying some stock. You have a 120-pa=
ge slide deck about how the company should make changes. You=E2=80=99ll hav=
e to go in and have a contentious meeting with management, and they might s=
ay no, and then you=E2=80=99d have to have a proxy fight, and you might los=
e. Even if you win, they=E2=80=99ll have to execute your plan; they might m=
ess it up, or your plan might be bad to begin with. Everything is risky and=
 uncertain and a lot of work, and it=E2=80=99ll be a year or two before you=
 know the results. Meanwhile the stock jumped 20% on your announcement, so =
you have a $20 million profit=C2=A0right now. If you just sell your stock, =
then, boom, you=E2=80=99ve made money from your activism=C2=A0without actua=
lly doing it,=C2=A0quickly, without much risk. Why not just sell now?
A little bit of the answer is =E2=80=9Cif you sell people will complain abo=
ut market manipulation,=E2=80=9D but most of the answer is that you are pla=
ying a repeated game, and your reputation is valuable.=C2=A0If you have a r=
eputation for being good at activism, you can keep doing activism, and it c=
an keep making you money. If you do this stunt =E2=80=94=C2=A0announce an a=
ctivist position, see the stock rise, dump the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0more th=
an once or twice, then the magic ends. After that, everyone will say =E2=80=
=9Coh, sure, you bought stock, but just to pump it, not to do valuable acti=
vism, I=E2=80=99m not falling for that again,=E2=80=9D and they won=E2=80=
=99t buy the stock, so it won=E2=80=99t go up, so you won=E2=80=99t have an=
y profit, so you=E2=80=99ll have to go back to actually doing activism =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0except that no one will trust you and they=E2=80=99ll all assum=
e you=E2=80=99re an opportunist.
In 2020, Chewy founder Ryan Cohen bought a big chunk of GameStop Corp. stoc=
k and did some activism to try to pivot it to e-commerce and technology. Th=
is was fine, you know, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0Cohen got himself a board se=
at and the company=E2=80=99s attention =E2=80=94=C2=A0until January 2021, w=
hen GameStop=E2=80=99s stock exploded. I  wrote at the time:

He=E2=80=99s been on the board for two weeks, he=E2=80=99s done roughly not=
hing, and he=E2=80=99s up 1,655%, or some other comically large number, dep=
ending on what minute you choose to look at the stock price. It is a stagge=
ringly good trade. =E2=80=A6 Cohen has been in for five months and has made=
 more than a billion dollars.
But what can he do? I mean one thing that he can do is work diligently on G=
ameStop=E2=80=99s board of directors to improve the company=E2=80=99s perfo=
rmance, like he planned to do two weeks ago. But it=E2=80=99s going to be k=
ind of a long time, if ever, before GameStop=E2=80=99s performance catches =
up to its stock price. The market has (let=E2=80=99s say!) already given Co=
hen full credit for unprecedented, spectacular, sustained success in turnin=
g GameStop around; it seems sort of tedious, now, to come to work every day=
 and try to actually do it. Also it might not work, and then where will he =
be? Not up $1.3 billion anyway.=C2=A0
The obvious trade is to get out while the getting is good, sell all his sto=
ck, quit the board and take a month-long victory lap just hanging out on Re=
ddit and bragging. But he can=E2=80=99t really do that either. For one thin=
g there would be certain legal complications if a board member and 12.9% sh=
areholder tried to dump all his stock into this wild rally. There is also t=
he likelihood that the GameStop magic is delicate, and if he announced he w=
as selling his stake the stock might collapse before he could sell.=C2=A0It=
=E2=80=99s not that the stock rallied this week because of Cohen=E2=80=99s =
involvement, but Cohen=E2=80=99s involvement is a load-bearing element some=
where down in the basement of this bizarre structure. If he said =E2=80=9Ct=
hat=E2=80=99s it I=E2=80=99m out,=E2=80=9D other people might too. He has m=
ade a once-in-a-lifetime trade and can=E2=80=99t cash in.=C2=A0

Well!  Here=E2=80=99s a story about Cohen from today=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Wall St=
reet Journal:

