The most interesting field of economics might be the economics of not doing=
 things. The main way that people make money, in the world, is by doing thi=
ngs that other people want: drilling oil, brewing coffee, maintaining socia=
l media sites, writing newsletters. But there are a few lines of business w=
here you can get paid for not=C2=A0doing things that you=E2=80=99d otherwis=
e do. Blackmail, for instance, is a classic: =E2=80=9CI will go around dist=
ributing these compromising photos of you, unless you pay me money, in whic=
h case I will do nothing.=E2=80=9D  Coasean bargaining: =E2=80=9CI will bui=
ld a smelly polluting factory on my land next to yours, unless you pay me m=
oney not to, in which case I will leave it undeveloped.=E2=80=9D Demand res=
ponse in electric grids: =E2=80=9CI will turn my lights on and use electric=
ity, unless you pay me not to, in which case I will use less electricity.=
=E2=80=9D And, in the modern world, all sorts of environmental credit schem=
es: =E2=80=9CI will  chop down these trees, drill this oil, etc., unless yo=
u pay me not to, in which case I won=E2=80=99t do anything at all.=E2=80=9D
There are so many ways in which the economics here are unintuitive. Conside=
r the oil market. There is some demand schedule for oil;=C2=A0people will u=
se more of it at lower prices and less at higher prices. There is also a su=
pply schedule: Some oil is cheaper to drill than other oil, so when oil pri=
ces are low only the cheapest-to-extract oil will get drilled, but when pri=
ces get high people will drill in more difficult environments because it be=
comes=C2=A0worth it. But then consider the market for=C2=A0not=C2=A0drillin=
g oil. If you own a bunch of oil fields, and someone will pay you $5 per ba=
rrel not to drill oil, you should start your not-drilling in the most-expen=
sive-to-drill places. =E2=80=9CGood news,=E2=80=9D you say, =E2=80=9CI have=
 decided not to drill in this field that costs $150 per barrel to drill, no=
w pay me my $5.=E2=80=9D You could expand on this theory. If you=C2=A0don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0own any oil fields, you could walk into the offices of some=
 environmental-credits company and say =E2=80=9Cif you pay me $5 per barrel=
 not to drill oil, I won=E2=80=99t go around buying oil fields and drilling=
 them.=E2=80=9D
Also consider the demand schedule there. If you promise me not to drill for=
 oil, I might pay you $5 per barrel for the oil you don=E2=80=99t drill. Bu=
t you could go to someone else and promise not to drill the oil, and they m=
ight pay you $3 per barrel. For the same barrels. =E2=80=9CNot drilling oil=
=E2=80=9D is a non-rival good; you can not drill the same barrel of oil as =
many times as you like, and sell it to a different person each time.
Or consider blackmail. If you get some compromising photos of me, and I pay=
 you not to publish them, then you won=E2=80=99t publish them (let=E2=80=99=
s assume). But what are your long-term incentives? The way to succeed in th=
e business of not publishing compromising photos is by=C2=A0taking lots of =
compromising photos and repeatedly threatening to publish them. If I paid y=
ou $100 not to publish the photos, and you were like =E2=80=9Cright, good, =
I get paid not to publish photos, I will stop taking the photos,=E2=80=9D y=
ou would be deeply misunderstanding your business. You are not being paid t=
o not publish photos =E2=80=94=C2=A0anyone can not publish photos! You are =
being paid to credibly threaten to publish photos, and then not publish the=
m.
This has important implications for the environmental credit schemes. You d=
on=E2=80=99t get paid for not drilling oil or not cutting down trees; you g=
et paid when there is a credible threat (from you or someone else) to drill=
 the oil or cut the trees, and you prevent it. You are in the credible-thre=
ats business.=C2=A0
Anyway I enjoyed this story about =E2=80=9C Crypto and climate change: can =
web3 help get us to net zero?,=E2=80=9D not so much for the crypto stuff as=
 for the credible-threats stuff:

Last year, a British oil exploration company and a tech start-up joined for=
ces on a project to permanently lock away untapped fossil fuel reserves in =
Greenland.
The idea was simple: the energy company, Greenland Gas and Oil, would not e=
xtract oil from an area on the east coast that it had exploration licences =
for. Instead it would monetise keeping the oil in the ground via a partners=
hip with the tech company, Carbonbase, which works on offsetting carbon emi=
ssions.
The mechanics were more complex. The partnership aimed to sell NFTs, digita=
l collectibles that come with ownership certificates, linked to the unexplo=
red land. The profits would then be used in part to compensate the energy c=
