<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if Elon Musk had never made a hostile bid=
 to buy Twitter Inc.? What if Twitter was just bopping along, being a publi=
c company, and then one day its former head of security, Peiter =E2=80=9CMu=
dge=E2=80=9D Zatko, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/28895329.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3RvbnBvc3QuY29tL3RlY2hub2xvZ3kva=
W50ZXJhY3RpdmUvMjAyMi90d2l0dGVyLXdoaXN0bGVibG93ZXItc2VjLXNwYW0v/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB564345e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> sent a bunch of regulators=C2=A0a whistle-=
blower letter</a> saying that Twitter=E2=80=99s=C2=A0security was bad in va=
rious ways, that it failed to safeguard user data and was vulnerable to hac=
kers and was generally sort of sloppy about stuff? Obviously some things wo=
uld happen:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Federal=
 Trade Commission, the Securities and Exchange Commission, etc. =E2=80=94 w=
ould investigate. If Twitter=E2=80=99s security was bad in the ways that Za=
tko says, then perhaps there would be fines, or settlements requiring Twitt=
er to change its practices.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
Politicians would hold hearings. Obviously politicians love to hold hearing=
s about how social-media companies are bad at privacy or moderation, so the=
y=E2=80=99d do that here. It seems unlikely that anything would come of thi=
s.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Perhaps there would be business=
 consequences. Twitter users, disgusted by its lax security practices, migh=
t quit. Advertisers might stop buying ads.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Given these things =E2=80=94=C2=A0investigations, potential =
fines, bad publicity, business consequences =E2=80=94=C2=A0there would=C2=
=A0<em>definitely=C2=A0</em>be shareholder lawsuits. Everything,=C2=A0I am =
always saying around here, is securities fraud: If a public company does a =
bad thing (bad information security practices, etc.), then shareholders can=
 sue, saying =E2=80=9Cyou did a bad thing but didn=E2=80=99t tell me about =
it, so I was tricked into buying stock, which is fraud.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What would be the aggregate impact of all of t=
hose things? Well, I don=E2=80=99t know; it depends on how true and how ser=
ious Zatko=E2=80=99s claims turn out to be. Twitter denies and downplays th=
em, while Zatko has incentives to play them up. But so far my sense is that=
 all of this is pretty ordinary-course stuff. If you are a large social med=
ia company, there will be internal controversies about your information-sec=
urity and content-moderation practices; every big social media company face=
s tradeoffs there. The people who lose out in those controversies will have=
 incentives to go public as whistle-blowers, and then regulators and politi=
cians will have incentives to investigate and extract settlements. None of =
this is=C2=A0<em>existential</em>; none of it is, like, =E2=80=9C90% of Twi=
tter users are bots and so advertisers=C2=A0will all leave,=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9CTwitter sold all of its users=E2=80=99 Social Security numbers to Nor=
th Korean hackers so the users will all quit,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CTwitter =
is operating illegally and will be shut down by the government.=E2=80=9D An=
d most of it is pretty hypothetical, more =E2=80=9CTwitter=E2=80=99s practi=
ces create risks of something really bad happening=E2=80=9D than =E2=80=9Cs=
omething really bad has actually happened.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily mean that all=
 of Zatko=E2=80=99s complaints are wrong or trivial. It=E2=80=99s just that=
, in a world where Twitter was just a public company with an information-se=
curity whistle-blower, the consequences of that would be pretty bounded. Mi=
ght Twitter pay, I don=E2=80=99t know, nine digits of fines? Might it lose =
some business? Might its stock drop by 5%? Might a shareholder lawsuit sett=
le for another nine digits? Again, without really having a strong view on t=
he validity or seriousness of these claims, I will say: Sure, those things =
are possible.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Might Twitter pay 11 digits of fines? Might it=
 lose 30% of its business? Might its stock drop by 30%? From <em>this</em> =
complaint? No, I am going to say, not really. It=E2=80=99s not literally im=
possible, but it=E2=80=99s not really a thing that happens. In particular, =
people don=E2=80=99t roll the dice on big investigations and lawsuits. They=
 settle, for reasonable amounts of money. There is a sense in which a certa=
in amount of regulatory fines and congressional hearings and shareholder la=
wsuits are a cost of doing business for big tech companies: They can be exp=
ensive and annoying and one tries to minimize them, but you can=E2=80=99t e=
xpect to escape them entirely, or worry=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>much about t=
hem when they happen. This stuff seems to be in that category.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in the actual world we live in, where Musk=
 <em>did=C2=A0</em>sign an agreement to buy Twitter that he is now trying t=
o get out of, things are different. Twitter,=C2=A0now, is pretty much a bin=
ary bet. Either Musk will buy Twitter for $54.20 per share in cash, as he a=
greed to do in April, or he won=E2=80=99t. If he does, Twitter is worth $54=
.20 per share, to its existing shareholders, and all this information-secur=
ity stuff is Elon Musk=E2=80=99s (bounded, manageable) problem. If he doesn=
=E2=80=99t, then Twitter is worth=C2=A0<em>much less=C2=A0</em>than $54.20 =
per share. What that number is =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe it is $25? $30?=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0will depend on Twitter=E2=80=99s user growth and ad revenue =
and business prospects and legal liabilities and so forth, and perhaps Zatk=
o=E2=80=99s complaints will lower that number by a dollar or two. But if yo=
u are a Twitter shareholder, that is a secondary concern; what is much more=
 important to you is that $54.20 is much much bigger than whatever that num=
ber is. You want the $54.20.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint might make it ha=
rder for you to get it. Yesterday Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2Vj=
Lmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMDk1NzY1L3RtMjI=
yNDc5MGQxX2V4OTktcS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB61882005" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> sent T=
witter another letter</a>, re-terminating the merger agreement, arguing tha=
t=C2=A0Twitter has breached the merger agreement in various ways based on Z=
atko=E2=80=99s complaint, which Musk say =E2=80=9Calleges far-reaching misc=
onduct at Twitter =E2=80=A6 that is likely to have severe consequences for =
Twitter=E2=80=99s business.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0(Twitter <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi=
9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMjMzNDcxL2QzNTk5MzdkZ=
GVmYTE0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb0e63b5d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> sent a letter ba=
ck to Musk</a> saying =E2=80=9Cno.=E2=80=9D) Like Musk=E2=80=99s previous l=
etter terminating the merger agreement for an unrelated list of reasons, th=
is letter is a strange piece of work =E2=80=94=C2=A0it misrepresents what t=
he merger agreement says for some reason?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it certainly says a lot of things. If Zatko=E2=
=80=99s complaints are all true and maximally bad, then, <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjkvbXVzay10cmllcy1hLW5ldy1=
3YXktb3V0LW9mLXR3aXR0ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgzMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwODMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
j1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB21a50218" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  as we discusse=
d yesterday</a>, Musk might have some argument that he can get out of the d=
eal for fraud. He=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>also have an argument that he ca=
n get out of the deal for some failure of Twitter=E2=80=99s representations=
 in the merger agreement, and this letter opens up that argument.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Will it work? Man, I have no idea. When Musk p=
reviously tried to terminate the merger agreement, Twitter sued to force hi=
m to close, and that case is moving toward a trial in October. It would be =
very hard to accommodate a whole new set of issues =E2=80=94=C2=A0How bad i=
s Twitter=E2=80=99s security? Is it true that =E2=80=9CTwitter apparently n=
ever acquired the rights to Twitter=E2=80=99s core machine learning models,=
=E2=80=9D as Musk=E2=80=99s new letter says?<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Who knew what, when? Will any of this have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial ad=
verse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter=E2=80=99s business? =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the =
six weeks or so before trial, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMzAvbXVzay1zZWVrcy10by1hbWVuZC10d2l0dGVyLWNvbXBsYWludC=
1pbi1zZWFsZWQtY291cnQtZmlsaW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MzAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZ=
