<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic business of an activist investor is =
that you pick a public company, you buy a bunch of its stock, you announce =
your position, you say =E2=80=9CI have a few suggestions for how this compa=
ny could be run better,=E2=80=9D you get the company to implement your sugg=
estions (by persuasiveness, or public pressure, or proxy fight),=C2=A0the s=
uggestions are in fact good, and the stock goes up. Your suggestions increa=
se the long-term value of the company, which is good for the stock price to=
day. You are a big shareholder, so you profit. When you are done =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0when the company has implemented your changes and the stock price ref=
lects the increased long-term value =E2=80=94=C2=A0you sell your stock and =
collect, as it were, your paycheck for a job well done.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously it is possible to be bad at this. Yo=
u might be bad at getting companies to implement your suggestions =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0you are not persuasive, you don=E2=80=99t win proxy fights, people do=
n=E2=80=99t like you, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0or you might be good at getting t=
hem to implement your suggestions, but the suggestions are bad and make the=
 stock go down. But let=E2=80=99s assume that some people are good at it. W=
hat that means is that, when they announce an activist position in a compan=
y=E2=80=99s stock, (1) they are likely to make changes to that company and =
(2) those changes are likely to make the stock go up.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>means is that, wh=
en they announce an activist position in a company=E2=80=99s stock, the sto=
ck will go up right away. <em>Other</em> investors will say =E2=80=9Cah, ye=
s, that activist is in the stock, and her track record is good, so this sto=
ck will go up, so I should buy it now,=E2=80=9D so they do, so it goes up n=
ow.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a good activist, this might create =
some temptation. You just spent, I don=E2=80=99t know, $100 million buying =
some stock. You have a 120-page slide deck about how the company should mak=
e changes. You=E2=80=99ll have to go in and have a contentious meeting with=
 management, and they might say no, and then you=E2=80=99d have to have a p=
roxy fight, and you might lose. Even if you win, they=E2=80=99ll have to ex=
ecute your plan; they might mess it up, or your plan might be bad to begin =
with. Everything is risky and uncertain and a lot of work, and it=E2=80=99l=
l be a year or two before you know the results. Meanwhile the stock jumped =
20% on your announcement, so you have a $20 million profit=C2=A0<em>right n=
ow</em>. If you just sell your stock, then, boom, you=E2=80=99ve made money=
 from your activism=C2=A0<em>without actually doing it,=C2=A0</em>quickly, =
without much risk. Why not just sell now?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A little bit of the answer is =E2=80=9Cif you =
sell people will complain about market manipulation,=E2=80=9D but most of t=
he answer is that you are playing a repeated game, and your reputation is v=
aluable.=C2=A0If you have a reputation for being good at activism, you can =
keep doing activism, and it can keep making you money. If you do this stunt=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0announce an activist position, see the stock rise, dump the=
 stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0more than once or twice, then the magic ends. After t=
hat, everyone will say =E2=80=9Coh, sure, you bought stock, but just to pum=
p it, not to do valuable activism, I=E2=80=99m not falling for that again,=
=E2=80=9D and they won=E2=80=99t buy the stock, so it won=E2=80=99t go up, =
so you won=E2=80=99t have any profit, so you=E2=80=99ll have to go back to =
actually doing activism =E2=80=94=C2=A0except that no one will trust you an=
d they=E2=80=99ll all assume you=E2=80=99re an opportunist.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2020, Chewy founder Ryan Cohen bought a big=
 chunk of GameStop Corp. stock and did some activism to try to pivot it to =
e-commerce and technology. This was fine, you know, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0Cohen got himself a board seat and the company=E2=80=99s attention =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0until January 2021, when GameStop=E2=80=99s stock exploded. I <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjcvcmVkZG=
l0LWRyaXZlbi1zdXJnZS1wdXRzLWdhbWVzdG9wLWFuZC1yeWFuLWNvaGVuLWluLWEtd2VpcmQtc=
3BvdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODMwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3Vy=
Y2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA4MzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeca5db42" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote at the time</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He=E2=80=99s been on the board for two weeks, =
he=E2=80=99s done roughly nothing, and he=E2=80=99s up 1,655%, or some othe=
r comically large number, depending on what minute you choose to look at th=
e stock price. It is a staggeringly good trade. =E2=80=A6 Cohen has been in=
 for five months and has made more than a billion dollars.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what can he do? I mean one thing that he c=
an do is work diligently on GameStop=E2=80=99s board of directors to improv=
e the company=E2=80=99s performance, like he planned to do two weeks ago. B=
ut it=E2=80=99s going to be kind of a long time, if ever, before GameStop=
=E2=80=99s performance catches up to its stock price. The market has (let=
=E2=80=99s say!) already given Cohen full credit for unprecedented, spectac=
ular, sustained success in turning GameStop around; it seems sort of tediou=
s, now, to come to work every day and try to actually do it. Also it might =
not work, and then where will he be? Not up $1.3 billion anyway.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The obvious trade is to get out while the gett=
ing is good, sell all his stock, quit the board and take a month-long victo=
ry lap just hanging out on Reddit and bragging. But he can=E2=80=99t really=
 do that either. For one thing there would be certain legal complications i=
f a board member and 12.9% shareholder tried to dump all his stock into thi=
s wild rally. There is also the likelihood that the GameStop magic is delic=
ate, and if he announced he was selling his stake the stock might collapse =
before he could sell.=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s not that the stock rallied this wee=
k because of Cohen=E2=80=99s involvement, but Cohen=E2=80=99s involvement i=
s a load-bearing element somewhere down in the basement of this bizarre str=
ucture. If he said =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s it I=E2=80=99m out,=E2=80=9D oth=
er people might too. He has made a once-in-a-lifetime trade and can=E2=80=
=99t cash in.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well! <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9yeW=
FuLWNvaGVucy1iZWQtYmF0aC1iZXlvbmQtc3RvY2stc2FsZXMtaGlnaGxpZ2h0LWdyYXktYXJlY=
S1pbi1kaXNjbG9zdXJlLTExNjYxNzMzNjY4P21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB78627e61" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Here=E2=80=99s a story about Cohen</a> fro=
m today=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Wall Street Journal:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investor Ryan Cohen might have run afoul of di=
sclosure guidelines in his surprise sale of Bed Bath &amp; Beyond Inc. stoc=
k this month, securities lawyers said, but regulatory action against him ap=
pears unlikely.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Cohen sold his entire stake in the home-go=
ods retailer on Aug. 16 and 17, just months after he took a significant pos=
ition in the company and pledged to force changes there. Shares tumbled aft=
er news of his sales came out on the afternoon of the 17th, but meanwhile M=
r. Cohen benefited from a huge surge in volume that enabled him to sell mil=
lions of shares while prices rose.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An ownership disclosure that Mr. Cohen filed o=
n the morning he began selling included a trivial update about the size of =
his holdings and said he hadn=E2=80=99t done any trading in Bed Bath &amp; =
Beyond during the prior 60 days. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Within minutes or hours of the ownership discl=
osure, Mr. Cohen began selling. Individual investors =E2=80=9Chave no idea =
he is dumping the stock against them,=E2=80=9D said Joshua Mitts, a law pro=
fessor at Columbia University who specializes in analytical research on tra=
ding strategies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission could i=
nvestigate whether Mr. Cohen had a plan to sell before he filed the Aug. 16=
 update that he should have disclosed, according to former regulators and l=
aw professors who specialize in securities law. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0A person fam=
iliar with Mr. Cohen=E2=80=99s trading said his filings complied with rules=
, and he didn=E2=80=99t make any offers or seek any prices for his Bed Bath=
 &amp; Beyond shares before making the Aug. 16 ownership disclosure update.=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdh=
