 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> filed an update</a> saying that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then the stock soared for, as far as anyone ca=
n tell, irrational meme-y reasons: The Aug. 16 filing reminded meme-stock i=
nvestors that Cohen owned a bunch of Bed Bath stock and options, and they w=
ere like =E2=80=9Coh yeah, love that guy, to the moon!=E2=80=9D: Cohen is a=
 =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329=
.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9yeWFuLWNvaGVuLXMtcmMtdmVudHV=
yZXMtc2VsbHMtZW50aXJlLXN0YWtlLWluLWJlZC1iYXRoLWJleW9uZC0xMTY2MDg1NTM3NQ/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafce71b5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">meme king</a>,=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=
=9Ca deep fan base of individual investors=E2=80=9D because of his role in =
GameStop, so when he buys a stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0or even just reminds peopl=
e that he already owned the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stock goes up. When Co=
hen filed that disclosure on the morning of Aug. 16, the stock was trading =
at around his purchase price; by the end of that day, it was way up. Cohen,=
 sensibly, sold, making a profit of about $57 million.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possibility is that this was a nefarious p=
lot, but that seems unlikely. The more likely explanation is that he felt r=
equired to make this disclosure and was not particularly planning to sell (=
at more or less no profit) when he made it. And then the stock soared and h=
e figured, sure, why not, take a profit now. People got excited when he rem=
inded them that he owned the stock, and he took advantage by selling the st=
ock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main point that I want to make here is tha=
t it is not at all clear that being a meme-stock king=C2=A0<em>is</em> a pa=
rticularly repeated game. I mean, Cohen has done it twice, so good for him.=
 But can he, or anyone,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0do it, like, four times? It is one thing to painstakingly build a=
 track record of driving corporate improvements through activism, to the po=
int that your investments can move a stock price, and then say =E2=80=9CI d=
o not want to undermine my credibility by dumping my stock before I have a =
chance to make improvements.=E2=80=9D It is another thing to build a track =
record of people on Reddit calling themselves =E2=80=9Capes=E2=80=9D and pi=
ling into your stock trades for entertainment reasons. How long can you cou=
nt on that lasting? If they=E2=80=99re buying your stock, you might as well=
 sell it.</p>
