<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most interesting field of economics might =
be the economics of not doing things. The main way that people make money, =
in the world, is by doing things that other people want: drilling oil, brew=
ing coffee, maintaining social media sites, writing newsletters. But there =
are a few lines of business where you can get paid for <em>not</em>=C2=A0do=
ing things that you=E2=80=99d otherwise do. Blackmail, for instance, is a c=
lassic: =E2=80=9CI will go around distributing these compromising photos of=
 you, unless you pay me money, in which case I will do nothing.=E2=80=9D <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQ29hc2VfdGhlb3JlbQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB8bf61fee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> Coasean bargaining</a>: =E2=80=9CI will build a sme=
lly polluting factory on my land next to yours, unless you pay me money not=
 to, in which case I will leave it undeveloped.=E2=80=9D Demand response in=
 electric grids: =E2=80=9CI will turn my lights on and use electricity, unl=
ess you pay me not to, in which case I will use less electricity.=E2=80=9D =
And, in the modern world, all sorts of environmental credit schemes: =E2=80=
=9CI will <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329=
.263565/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDQ=
tMjEvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYteW91LWNhbi1zZWxsLXRoZS10cmVlcy15b3UtZG9uLXQtY3V0P2NtcG=
lkPUJCRDA4MzAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzb=
GV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB71eae282" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> chop down these trees</a>, drill this oil, e=
tc., unless you pay me not to, in which case I won=E2=80=99t do anything at=
 all.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are so many ways in which the economics =
here are unintuitive. Consider the oil market. There is some demand schedul=
e for oil;=C2=A0people will use more of it at lower prices and less at high=
er prices. There is also a supply schedule: Some oil is cheaper to drill th=
an other oil, so when oil prices are low only the cheapest-to-extract oil w=
ill get drilled, but when prices get high people will drill in more difficu=
lt environments because it becomes=C2=A0worth it. But then consider the mar=
ket for=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>drilling oil. If you own a bunch of oil fiel=
ds, and someone will pay you $5 per barrel not to drill oil, you should sta=
rt your not-drilling in the most-expensive-to-drill places. =E2=80=9CGood n=
ews,=E2=80=9D you say, =E2=80=9CI have decided not to drill in this field t=
hat costs $150 per barrel to drill, now pay me my $5.=E2=80=9D You could ex=
pand on this theory. If you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>own any oil fi=
elds, you could walk into the offices of some environmental-credits company=
 and say =E2=80=9Cif you pay me $5 per barrel not to drill oil, I won=E2=80=
=99t go around buying oil fields and drilling them.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also consider the demand schedule there. If yo=
u promise me not to drill for oil, I might pay you $5 per barrel for the oi=
l you don=E2=80=99t drill. But you could go to someone else and promise not=
 to drill the oil, and they might pay you $3 per barrel. For the same barre=
ls. =E2=80=9CNot drilling oil=E2=80=9D is a non-rival good; you can not dri=
ll the same barrel of oil as many times as you like, and sell it to a diffe=
rent person each time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or consider blackmail. If you get some comprom=
ising photos of me, and I pay you not to publish them, then you won=E2=80=
=99t publish them (let=E2=80=99s assume). But what are your long-term incen=
tives? The way to succeed in the business of not publishing compromising ph=
otos is by=C2=A0<em>taking lots of compromising photos and repeatedly threa=
tening to publish them</em>. If I paid you $100 not to publish the photos, =
and you were like =E2=80=9Cright, good, I get paid not to publish photos, I=
 will stop taking the photos,=E2=80=9D you would be deeply misunderstanding=
 your business. You are not being paid to not publish photos =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0anyone can not publish photos! You are being paid to credibly threaten t=
o publish photos, and then not publish them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This has important implications for the enviro=
nmental credit schemes. You don=E2=80=99t get paid for not drilling oil or =
not cutting down trees; you get paid when there is a credible threat (from =
you or someone else) to drill the oil or cut the trees, and you prevent it.=
 You are in the credible-threats business.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway I enjoyed this story about =E2=80=9C<a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28895329.263565/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMWY3OTVlNWQtYzJjZi00ZTkxLTg5ZjEtNmQ1NTQ0YThh=
M2Ri/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe79f1fe4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Crypto and climate change:=
 can web3 help get us to net zero?</a>,=E2=80=9D not so much for the crypto=
 stuff as for the credible-threats stuff:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year, a British oil exploration company a=
nd a tech start-up joined forces on a project to permanently lock away unta=
pped fossil fuel reserves in Greenland.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea was simple: the energy company, Green=
land Gas and Oil, would not extract oil from an area on the east coast that=
 it had exploration licences for. Instead it would monetise keeping the oil=
 in the ground via a partnership with the tech company, Carbonbase, which w=
orks on offsetting carbon emissions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The mechanics were more complex. The partnersh=
ip aimed to sell NFTs, digital collectibles that come with ownership certif=
icates, linked to the unexplored land. The profits would then be used in pa=
rt to compensate the energy company and the oil would stay underground. And=
, since the Greenland government had stopped issuing new exploration licenc=
es, the energy company would not be able to simply apply for another and ta=
p a different part of the country. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, after months of discussions, the partners=
hip ran into problems. Carbonbase and Greenland Gas and Oil did not agree o=
n how to structure the joint venture. Carbonbase also discovered that the c=
ountry of Greenland had never successfully produced any oil, a fact that th=
ey said undermined the whole idea. Pursuing the project =E2=80=9Cwould have=
 destroyed our public reputation=E2=80=9D and looked like =E2=80=9Cgreenwas=
hing=E2=80=9D, says Max Song, founder of Carbonbase.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Someone should really pay me not to drill for =
oil in my backyard. Is there oil under my backyard? I don=E2=80=99t know, b=
ut someone should pay me not to find out.</p>
